1455":"1455","Abt 1464":"about 1464","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Saint Nicholas Church, Ipswich, Ipswich Borough, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Ipswich, Ipswich district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cutler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a maker of knives, from Middle English <i>cutele</i>, <i>cutteler</i>, <i>coteler</i> ‘cutler; maker, repairer, or seller of knives, etc.’ (Anglo-French <i>cuteler</i>, Old French <i>coutelier, cotelier</i>). Compare   Nesmith   and   Cottle  .","Americanized form of German   Kottler   or <b>Kattler</b>, which is of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Cuttler","meanings":["English: variant of   Cutler  ."]},{"name":"Nesmith","meanings":["English and Scottish (Glasgow): occupational name for a maker of knives, from Middle English <i>knif-smith</i> ‘knife-smith, cutler’ (Old English <i>cnīf</i> + <i>smith</i>).","English: alternatively, an occupational name connected with wheel making, from Middle English <i>nave-smith</i> ‘nave-smith’ (Old English <i>nafu</i>, <i>nafa</i> ‘nave, the central part of a wheel’ + <i>smith</i>)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Thomas Cutler was born about 1445, in Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Cutler I, was 26 and his mother, Mabel Benjamin, was 17. He married Dorthy Barker in 1470, in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1445–":"umbes 1445–Surnud","1445–Male":"1445–Surnud","1455–1474":"1455–1474","1445–Female":"1445–Surnud","1464–Male":"1464–Surnud","1466–Male":"1466–Surnud","1470–1523":"1470–1523","1420–1467":"1420–1467","1430–1480":"1430–1480","Abt 1445":"umbes 1445","Abt 1466":"umbes 1466","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","Abt 1470":"umbes 1470","1523":"1523","1445":"1445","1467":"1467","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","Abt 1464":"umbes 1464","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Saint Nicholas Church, Ipswich, Ipswich Borough, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ipswich, Ipswich district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1445–":"noin 1445–Kuollut","1445–Male":"1445–Kuollut","1455–1474":"1455–1474","1445–Female":"1445–Kuollut","1464–Male":"1464–Kuollut","1466–Male":"1466–Kuollut","1470–1523":"1470–1523","1420–1467":"1420–1467","1430–1480":"1430–1480","Abt 1445":"noin 1445